Welcome!

Operating systems are one of the most interesting and fundamental topics of CS. Without an OS, a computer would not be able to run any user applications 🤯. It’s also a challenging topic as it brings together pieces you already know about software and hardware, which should make this class a defining moment in your CS education!

Having worked on a variety of industrial, academical, and educational OSes and bootloaders, this topic has become one of my main fields of expertise during the past two decades. I’m therefore very excited to be teaching this class again this quarter, and to accompany you on this decisive journey.

Overview

Objectives

  • Study operating systems and their typical structure: kernel, processes, threads.
  • Apprehend the complexity of concurrency: threads and shared data, synchronization mechanisms, deadlocks.
  • Learn about data storage at both physical and logical levels.
  • Understand memory management using virtual memory.
  • Extensive programming at system level.

Prerequisites

Required: ECS 34 or ECS 36C or ECS 60

Expected knowledge/skills:

  • C programming on UNIX systems (including a good understanding of pointers)
  • Basic data structures (lists, queues, stacks, etc.) and basic notions of algorithm complexity
  • Use of make for build automation
  • Use of a source-level debugger such as gdb
  • Use of git as a version control and collaboration system
Required: ECS 154A or EEC 170

Expected knowledge/skills:

  • Binary/hexadecimal numeral notations
  • Principles of assembly language
  • Interrupts and interconnection hardware
  • Caching and memory hierarchy design

CS tutoring

Generally, we are lucky enough to have at least a couple of former students who are willing to be CS tutors for this class. Please keep in mind that tutors are not supposed to help you write your projects, their sole mission is to assist you in doing that yourself. Any failure in upholding appropriate behavior when using CS tutoring will be duly reported.

Look for tutors who are scheduled to cover 150 on the dedicated website.

It usually takes up to a couple of weeks after the beginning of the quarter for tutoring to officially start.

Lectures

All the lecture material (slides, and potential example code) will be made available for download on the same day as class.

You are expected to attend class, but attendance is not part of your final grade. However, it is your entire responsibility to keep track of the material discussed in class, as well as any announcements made in class.

During class, it is expected that you respect the few following rules:

  • Arrive on time. If you can’t make it on time, please make sure that your late arrival doesn’t disturb the ongoing class.
  • Don’t leave before the lecture is over. If you have an appointment that forces you to leave early, please give me a heads-up before lecture starts, and sit next to the door so that you don’t disturb the class when leaving.
  • Hold your conversation with your neighbors until class is over. You are more than welcome to actively participate during the class and about the material being presented, but telling your neighbor about your weekend can wait until the end of the class.
  • Avoid using electronic devices. Using electronic devices such as laptops, tablets or smartphones is discouraged during class. Many studies have shown that taking notes by hand helps students learn more efficiently, and it also keeps computers’ many available distractions at bay (NPR, NYT).
    • If you use your laptop, at least be nice and sit in the rear.

Failing to respect these rules and disturbing the class might result in you being respectfully asked to leave the classroom.

Textbook

No textbooks are required, but are recommended to complement class.

OS books

Operating Systems: Principles and Practice, 2nd edition [OSPP]

by Thomas Anderson and Michael Dahlin

One of the most recent and popular textbooks at the moment. Some of the lectures follow a similar outline.

Operating System Concepts, 9th edition [OSC]

by Avi Silberschatz, Peter Baer Galvin and Greg Gagne

Another typical and popular textbook for this type of class.

Operating Systems: Three Easy Pieces [OSTEP]

by Remzi H. Arpaci-Dusseau and Andrea C. Arpaci-Dusseau

A free textbook accessible online at http://pages.cs.wisc.edu/~remzi/OSTEP/.

Assessment

Class quizzes

To make sure that you keep up with class, there will be a small quiz to complete after each lecture and each discussion.

Lecture quizzes will be posted within a couple of hours after lecture and will be due the day before the following lecture (e.g., for a lecture on Monday, you have until Tuesday midnight).

Discussion quizzes will posted at the end of each week, on Fridays, and will be due on Tuesday of the following week.

Your four worst class quizzes (i.e., one full week worth of quizzes) will be dropped at the end of the quarter. So you can safely miss a few without any consequences.

Projects

The class includes three projects, which are to be worked in teams of exactly two students.

In order to make sure that you experience different group dynamics, you cannot have the same partner for more than two projects. That means that you need to switch partner at least once during the quarter.

Don’t wait the last minute to find a partner, and make sure that you find someone with whom you can work well!

For example, meet beforehand (in person or via video-call) and discuss how you envision your collaboration, what you expect from the class, what kind of grade you’d like to get, etc.

Most partnership failures I have seen over the years stemmed from partners who found each other randomly and did not make sure that their working style and skills were compatible.

Projects overview:

  • Project 1: simple shell
  • Project 2: user-level thread library
  • Project 3: custom file-system

Projects are about 2.5 weeks long and there are no slip days for any of the projects. Make sure that your projects are submitted before the indicated time on due dates to avoid any late penalties.

The penalty for late submissions is \(\frac{(1.3471^x - 1)}{(1.3471 - 1)}\) where \(x\) represents the number of decimal hours late.

For example, submitting 1.5 hours late will incur a penalty of 4.5%, while submitting 7.2 hours late will incur a penalty of 24.6%. The penalty exponentially reaches 100% after 12 hours.

The reference environment for projects is the CSIF, which is running Ubuntu 22.04 LTS. In other words, all the projects are expected to compile without warnings or errors and flawlessly work on CSIF computers. If you develop on your own computer, make sure to test thoroughly on CSIF computers (or equivalent) before submitting.

Please run your programs on CSIF computers before reporting any bugs on Piazza.

Project grading is split in two different aspects (for the first two projects):

Automatic grading: ~60%
  • Running a script against your implementation and checking multiple relevant test cases
  • Note that depending on the programming assignment, part of the testing script may be provided before the deadline
Manual review: ~40%
  • Checking the quality of your implementation: use of proper language constructs, data types, coding style, etc.
  • Note that some details about the rubrics will be provided on a per-assignment basis

The last project is fully auto-graded.

Interactive grading and groupwork

After each project, you will fill out a self and peer evaluation, to assess your own engagement/contribution in the project as well as your partner’s. At the end of the quarter, these evaluations will be compiled into a groupwork score.

During the last week of class (week #10), you will have individual interactive grading. During a 10-minute session, you will be asked questions about two of the projects in order to measure your overall understanding of the projects’ concepts, as well as the implementations you submitted.

Exams

There will be two midterm exams throughout the quarter, and one final exam.

Midterms are closed-book and usually cover the most recently studied class material.

The final exam covers the entire class (lectures, discussion sections, and projects), and you are allowed to bring a single double-sided 8.5-by-11-inch page of handwritten notes with you.

There are no make-up exams, unless you are sick on the day of the exam and can present a doctor’s note excusing you for that day.

Grading

Type Percentage
Class quizzes 10%
Midterms 20%
Final 20%
Projects 35%
Interactive grading and group work 15%
Total 100%
Participation +3% (extra credit)
  • Participation typically includes Piazza statistics and survey participation, etc.
  • The grade scale follows the default scheme: i.e., A+ = > 97%, A = 93%-96%, A- = 90%-92%, …, F = < 60%.
  • Sometimes projects or exams are curved (generally using a root curve) in order to obtain a mean of around 78%.
  • All scores entered on Canvas are always definitive scores; there is no further curving.

Regrades

Regrade requests should only focus on actual grading mistakes and should be thoroughly justified.

Examples of incorrect regrade requests:

  • Asking why your answer is wrong. Please ask for feedback during drop-in hours or on the class forum instead.
  • Explaining that your answer meant something else. You are graded on what you wrote, not what you had in mind.
  • Disagreeing on the number of deducted points. Rubrics apply uniformly to all students, and are therefore non-negotiable.

Regrade requests are to be submitted within 3 days after the grades are published for a midterm (via Gradescope) and 5 business days for a project (in person during drop-in hours). For the final exam, I usually try to allow a 6- to 12-hour time period for students to submit regrade requests if necessary.

Expected conduct

Students are expected to read the UC Davis Code of Conduct thoroughly and strictly follow it.

Any failure to respect the Code of Conduct will be reported to Student Judicial Affairs and usually results in both disciplinary and academic sanctions.

Some important rules for this class in particular are listed below.

Class material

  • Posting any class material online without the instructor’s consent is absolutely prohibited.
    • This includes uploading slides or project assignments on websites such as coursehero.com or chegg.com.
  • My course materials are protected by US copyright law and by University policy. I am the exclusive owner of the copyright in those materials I create.
  • You may not reproduce, distribute or display (post/upload) course materials in any way –whether or not a fee is charged– without my express prior written consent. You also may not allow others to do so. If you do so, you may be subject to student conduct proceedings under the UC Davis Code of Academic Conduct.

Projects

  • Projects are to be worked on in pairs, unless specified otherwise. Partners are expected to work collaboratively, and in similar proportions.
  • For students who previously took the class (or part of it), reusing your own work is strictly prohibited. All projects must be started from scratch.
  • Collaboration between students/groups is encouraged but discussion of projects should be limited to general discussion of topics (including past students).
  • Viewing other students’ submissions is strictly prohibited (including past students).
  • All submissions with be compared with MOSS in order to detect plagiarism with other students or with publicly available source code.
  • All online sources (stackoverflow, etc.) must be properly cited in submissions. Students are responsible for understanding all code cited, and may receive zero on a project for not knowing exactly how the code works.
  • Your project submissions are to be kept private and are not meant to be posted on publicly accessible websites or shared with other students, even after you graduate.

Exams

  • Exams are to be worked alone.
  • Collaboration with anyone else is not permitted.

Class forum

  • Follow the rules listed on the class forum.
  • You are training to be professionals and as such, you are expected to communicate in a professional manner. Stay courteous and polite to your peers.
  • Do not post code in the public forum (only high-level pseudo-code), or provide any elements of answer to any of the coursework.
  • Before asking a new question, please make sure that your question has not been asked and answered already (syllabus, announcements, slides, forum).

Cheating

  • There is a zero tolerance policy on cheating.
  • Any suspicion of cheating that is beyond reasonable doubt will be turned over to SJA for resolution.
  • If you are in violation of the Code of Conduct and have been referred to SJA, acknowledge your mistake, accept the punishment, learn from it, and move on.
